0
00:00:01,000 --> 00:00:04,000
Downloaded From www.AllSubs.org

1
00:01:39,240 --> 00:01:41,440
- Package for Robert Garfield.
- Yeah.

2
00:01:41,680 --> 00:01:45,000
- Sign here.
- Thanks.

3
00:02:37,840 --> 00:02:43,480
<i>Whenever it wants, the past can come
kicking the door down.</i>

4
00:02:43,720 --> 00:02:47,560
<i>And you never know
where it's gonna take you.</i>

5
00:02:47,800 --> 00:02:52,640
<i>All you can do is hope
it's a place you wanna go.</i>

6
00:03:03,240 --> 00:03:07,280
<i>You've reached the Garfield family.
Jill and the boys are away.</i>

7
00:03:07,520 --> 00:03:09,920
<i>You can reach them on their cells.</i>

8
00:03:10,160 --> 00:03:15,840
<i>I'll be on the road for a few days.
Be back Tuesday.</i>

9
00:03:19,720 --> 00:03:23,400
On behalf of the president
of the United States

10
00:03:23,640 --> 00:03:25,680
I present this flag

11
00:03:25,920 --> 00:03:28,280
for the honorable
service rendered

12
00:03:28,520 --> 00:03:31,920
by your husband,
Major John Sullivan.

13
00:03:32,160 --> 00:03:35,040
- Hey, Sully!
- Hey!

14
00:03:35,280 --> 00:03:38,720
Bobby, I decided what I wanna be.
A magician.

15
00:03:38,960 --> 00:03:43,120
- I'll pull rabbits out of a hat.
- Rabbits will shit in your hat.

16
00:03:43,360 --> 00:03:47,520
But I'd be a cool bastard.
Admit it.

17
00:03:56,640 --> 00:04:02,880
There's cake at the Veterans Hall.
Of course you're all welcome.

18
00:04:05,280 --> 00:04:07,480
- Mr. Garfield.
- Mr. Oliver.

19
00:04:07,720 --> 00:04:11,480
- Thanks for sending the glove.
- Been Sully's lawyer forever.

20
00:04:11,720 --> 00:04:16,800
Couldn't see why a baseball glove
had to go through probate.

21
00:04:17,040 --> 00:04:21,880
- You and Sully were kids together?
- Yeah, there were three of us.

22
00:04:22,120 --> 00:04:24,840
Me and Sully, and a girl named Carol.

23
00:04:25,080 --> 00:04:26,840
- Carol Gerber?
- That's right.

24
00:04:27,080 --> 00:04:30,520
I'm hoping she'll be here.

25
00:04:31,160 --> 00:04:35,080
You didn't hear about Carol?

26
00:04:35,880 --> 00:04:38,640
No.

27
00:04:40,800 --> 00:04:44,040
I'm afraid she's dead.

28
00:04:44,680 --> 00:04:47,680
I'm so sorry.

29
00:05:27,720 --> 00:05:30,840
<i>This street is where it all happened.</i>

30
00:05:31,080 --> 00:05:33,640
<i>It's not much now.</i>

31
00:05:33,880 --> 00:05:37,680
<i>Why do we always expect home
will stay the same?</i>

32
00:05:37,920 --> 00:05:41,280
<i>Nothing else does.</i>

33
00:05:51,320 --> 00:05:56,640
<i>It's funny how when you're a kid,
a day can last forever.</i>

34
00:05:56,880 --> 00:06:02,800
<i>Now, all these years
seem just like a blink.</i>

35
00:06:44,360 --> 00:06:46,480
<i>Bobby? Bobby-o?</i>

36
00:06:46,720 --> 00:06:48,040
Time to get a wiggle on.

37
00:06:48,280 --> 00:06:51,560
Wake up, Bobby.

38
00:06:52,640 --> 00:06:55,240
Hey, wait for me!

39
00:06:56,720 --> 00:06:59,840
Come on, Johnny.

40
00:07:08,120 --> 00:07:12,360
Happy birthday, Mr. Eleven. Ta-da!

41
00:07:18,880 --> 00:07:22,280
Oh, wow. Library card.

42
00:07:22,520 --> 00:07:27,800
A grownup's library card,
if you please.

43
00:07:28,840 --> 00:07:30,960
Thanks, Mom.

44
00:07:31,200 --> 00:07:32,920
- Is...?
- Don't.

45
00:07:33,160 --> 00:07:37,080
Don't you think I wanted to get you
a bike? I can't afford it.

46
00:07:37,320 --> 00:07:41,400
Know how that makes me feel?
Your father didn't leave us well-off.

47
00:07:41,640 --> 00:07:44,600
He did leave us three months'
unpaid rent

48
00:07:44,840 --> 00:07:48,440
a life insurance policy that lapsed
before he died.

49
00:07:48,680 --> 00:07:52,000
He left a rather large stack
of unpaid bills

50
00:07:52,240 --> 00:07:54,360
which I managed to take care of.

51
00:07:54,600 --> 00:07:57,160
People understand our situation.

52
00:07:57,400 --> 00:07:59,440
Mr. Biderman is a good example

53
00:07:59,680 --> 00:08:02,840
but it has not been easy.
Do you get that?

54
00:08:03,080 --> 00:08:07,480
Your father never met
an inside straight he didn't like.

55
00:08:07,720 --> 00:08:10,960
- What's an inside straight?
- Never you mind, Bobby-o.

56
00:08:11,200 --> 00:08:16,720
Don't let me catch you playing cards.
I've had enough of that.

57
00:08:16,960 --> 00:08:19,840
Come on, then.

58
00:08:20,680 --> 00:08:24,000
That must be the new
upstairs apartment tenant.

59
00:08:24,240 --> 00:08:28,800
I don't trust people who move their
things in paper bags. It's slutty.

60
00:08:29,040 --> 00:08:32,680
- He has suitcases.
- Yes, but they don't match, do they?

61
00:08:32,920 --> 00:08:35,520
Oh, hello, folks. I'm Ted Brautigan.

62
00:08:35,760 --> 00:08:37,520
I'll be living upstairs.

63
00:08:37,760 --> 00:08:40,560
I'm Elizabeth Garfield.
This is my son, Robert.

64
00:08:40,800 --> 00:08:43,320
<i>Nice to meet you, Mr. Brattigan.
Tempus fugit.</i>

65
00:08:43,560 --> 00:08:46,440
It's Brautigan,
but Ted is fine with me.

66
00:08:46,680 --> 00:08:50,280
It's nice to meet you.
I hope you like it here.

67
00:08:50,520 --> 00:08:53,400
Thank you, Robert.

68
00:08:56,360 --> 00:08:58,320
Birthday boy!

69
00:08:58,560 --> 00:09:01,640
Carol, it's hard enough
being friends without that.

70
00:09:01,880 --> 00:09:04,680
You loved it. Here.

71
00:09:04,920 --> 00:09:07,640
- Is this gonna be gushy?
- I don't know.

72
00:09:07,880 --> 00:09:11,040
Better not be.

73
00:09:11,840 --> 00:09:12,760
Whoa.

74
00:09:13,000 --> 00:09:16,720
- Just like it.
- Yeah, that's great.

75
00:09:16,920 --> 00:09:20,120
- Thanks.
- Sure.

76
00:09:21,240 --> 00:09:25,400
- Didn't get the bike, did you?
- No big deal. Mom can't afford it.

77
00:09:25,640 --> 00:09:26,840
She buys new dresses.

78
00:09:27,080 --> 00:09:32,560
She has to look nice for the office.
Are you coming?

79
00:09:32,600 --> 00:09:35,760
- Yeah.
- Come on.

80
00:09:41,160 --> 00:09:44,560
- Hey, Sully!
- Hey!

81
00:09:47,280 --> 00:09:48,440
- Get the bike?
- No.

82
00:09:48,680 --> 00:09:53,880
Well, I got nothing for you.
But happy birthday!

83
00:10:00,080 --> 00:10:03,680
Hang on! Wait for me!

84
00:10:27,840 --> 00:10:31,480
- What's an inside straight?
- Something to do with gambling.

85
00:10:31,720 --> 00:10:37,560
Poker. You draw a middle card.
It's dumb, strictly for suckers.

86
00:10:43,000 --> 00:10:45,960
<i>This neighborhood
is getting terribly run-down.</i>

87
00:10:46,200 --> 00:10:49,720
<i>I think I'll have to move.</i>

88
00:10:54,760 --> 00:10:57,240
<i>- Yeah?
- Is that how we answer the phone?</i>

89
00:10:57,480 --> 00:11:02,600
Hi, Mom. I'm sorry. I was just excited
about dinner and all.

90
00:11:02,840 --> 00:11:07,120
Mr. Biderman has to work late
and needs me to do the same.

91
00:11:07,360 --> 00:11:10,040
So birthday dinner
at the Colony is off.

92
00:11:10,280 --> 00:11:11,240
<i>Okay, Mom.</i>

93
00:11:11,480 --> 00:11:15,080
There are leftovers.
I'll be home to tuck you in.

94
00:11:15,320 --> 00:11:18,120
Oh, make sure to turn
off the gas ring

95
00:11:18,360 --> 00:11:20,480
<i>when you're done with the stove.</i>

96
00:11:20,720 --> 00:11:25,000
- I know.
- See you soon.

97
00:11:40,480 --> 00:11:42,360
Evening, Robert.

98
00:11:42,600 --> 00:11:44,360
Or should I say Bobby?

99
00:11:44,600 --> 00:11:47,320
Oh, Mr. Brautigan. Hi.

100
00:11:47,560 --> 00:11:50,240
It's Ted.

101
00:11:50,360 --> 00:11:55,280
Sorry. Ted'll be hard for me,
but I'll try.

102
00:11:55,520 --> 00:11:58,720
You going out later?

103
00:11:59,760 --> 00:12:02,480
I was supposed to have
a birthday dinner.

104
00:12:02,720 --> 00:12:07,960
Mom had to stay at work,
even though she didn't want to.

105
00:12:08,960 --> 00:12:12,120
Are you a rich man then

106
00:12:12,360 --> 00:12:15,680
from your birthday gifts?

107
00:12:19,320 --> 00:12:21,520
A library card?

108
00:12:21,760 --> 00:12:24,640
No, an adult library card. Oh, my.

109
00:12:24,880 --> 00:12:27,440
All the master storytellers
waiting for you.

110
00:12:27,680 --> 00:12:32,000
You know why she picked it?
Because it was free.

111
00:12:32,240 --> 00:12:35,720
That doesn't matter.
Don't you give up on this card.

112
00:12:35,960 --> 00:12:38,640
Because books can be solid gold.

113
00:12:38,880 --> 00:12:43,320
The great ones have gotten us
through the nights for centuries.

114
00:12:43,560 --> 00:12:48,440
Give a writer an hour to hook you.
If he can't, find someone else.

115
00:12:48,680 --> 00:12:51,280
Think you can try that?

116
00:12:51,520 --> 00:12:54,320
If I don't have anything else to do.

117
00:12:54,560 --> 00:12:57,120
Fair enough. Don't be afraid.

118
00:12:57,360 --> 00:13:01,280
"A Tale of Two Cities" ends
with a beheading, great stuff.

119
00:13:01,520 --> 00:13:07,640
"Lost Horizon", magic and places
unknown. Can't beat that.

120
00:13:07,920 --> 00:13:12,400
Where'd you live before
you came here, Mr...? Ted?

121
00:13:12,640 --> 00:13:16,280
Some other place
that wasn't as nice as this.

122
00:13:16,520 --> 00:13:18,680
You lived here long?

123
00:13:18,920 --> 00:13:22,400
Yes, sir. Since my dad died.

124
00:13:22,640 --> 00:13:26,480
- When was that sad day?
- When I was 5.

125
00:13:26,720 --> 00:13:29,000
Six years, huh?

126
00:13:29,240 --> 00:13:32,280
You must know everything happening
on this street.

127
00:13:32,520 --> 00:13:39,360
Sure do. Because nothing happens
on this street.

128
00:13:41,000 --> 00:13:44,360
- Six years.
- That's just a blink.

129
00:13:44,600 --> 00:13:47,480
Someday you'll agree.

130
00:13:47,720 --> 00:13:52,440
You know, Ben Jonson called time
"the old bald cheater".

131
00:13:52,680 --> 00:13:53,680
What?

132
00:13:53,920 --> 00:13:57,640
Ben Jonson called time
"the old bald cheater".

133
00:13:57,880 --> 00:13:59,360
I like that.

134
00:13:59,600 --> 00:14:03,640
I think I do too. Who's Ben Jonson?

135
00:14:03,880 --> 00:14:07,160
He's an English writer,
dead these many years.

136
00:14:07,400 --> 00:14:09,680
Brilliant, but foolish about money.

137
00:14:09,920 --> 00:14:13,600
And given to flatulence.

138
00:14:13,840 --> 00:14:17,280
What's flatulence?

139
00:14:23,640 --> 00:14:27,600
Yeah, kids always think
farts are funny.

140
00:14:29,600 --> 00:14:33,720
Might have a job for you.
Have to think about it first.

141
00:14:33,960 --> 00:14:35,280
Really?

142
00:14:35,520 --> 00:14:40,360
Yeah. If it works out,
you might get that bike.

143
00:14:42,960 --> 00:14:45,960
How'd you know I wanted a bike?

144
00:14:46,200 --> 00:14:49,440
All kids want bikes.

145
00:15:17,760 --> 00:15:20,760
Hey, Mom. I took another look
at that bike.

146
00:15:21,000 --> 00:15:25,320
It's a Phantom, 26-incher. Real swell.

147
00:15:25,560 --> 00:15:28,640
No, perfect. Perfect is more like it.

148
00:15:28,880 --> 00:15:32,400
Start saving those pennies.

149
00:15:33,040 --> 00:15:35,440
Ted? It's me.

150
00:15:35,680 --> 00:15:36,680
Hi, kid. Come in.

151
00:15:36,920 --> 00:15:39,480
Thanks for making the skyward journey.

152
00:15:39,720 --> 00:15:42,280
An icy root beer awaits you as reward.

153
00:15:42,520 --> 00:15:45,720
The colder, the better.

154
00:15:45,880 --> 00:15:49,640
One feels them first at the back
of one's eyes.

155
00:15:49,880 --> 00:15:52,800
Feels what?

156
00:15:53,640 --> 00:15:58,280
One feels them first
at the back of one's eyes.

157
00:16:02,040 --> 00:16:04,640
Yeah.

158
00:16:05,760 --> 00:16:07,680
Hey, I did like you said.

159
00:16:07,920 --> 00:16:10,080
- What?
- I gave him a couple of hours.

160
00:16:10,320 --> 00:16:13,400
Oh, yeah. "Lost Horizon".
What do you think?

161
00:16:13,640 --> 00:16:15,360
Better than the "Hardy Boys".

162
00:16:15,600 --> 00:16:18,560
Yeah, sure is.

163
00:16:20,160 --> 00:16:24,680
Tell me, Bobby, how'd you like
to make a dollar a week?

164
00:16:24,920 --> 00:16:26,080
Would I ever?!

165
00:16:26,320 --> 00:16:28,840
Well, my eyes are beginning
to fail me

166
00:16:29,080 --> 00:16:33,960
and if you will read me
the "Harwich Journal" every day

167
00:16:34,200 --> 00:16:37,160
headline stuff, sports,
comics, want ads

168
00:16:37,400 --> 00:16:42,120
I'll give you said dollar.
What do you say?

169
00:16:43,280 --> 00:16:44,680
What else?

170
00:16:44,920 --> 00:16:46,080
What do you mean?

171
00:16:46,320 --> 00:16:50,280
There's got to be more
to it than that.

172
00:16:50,360 --> 00:16:53,640
Yeah, there is.

173
00:16:53,800 --> 00:16:56,520
So, what's the real job?

174
00:16:56,760 --> 00:16:58,720
Keep your eyes open.

175
00:16:58,960 --> 00:17:02,920
- For what?
- Low men.

176
00:17:03,160 --> 00:17:05,720
That's right, Bobby.

177
00:17:05,960 --> 00:17:09,360
I use the term "low"
in the Dickensian sense

178
00:17:09,600 --> 00:17:14,480
meaning dangerous. Men who stop
at nothing to get what they want.

179
00:17:14,720 --> 00:17:17,920
Your real job will simply be

180
00:17:18,160 --> 00:17:20,680
to walk around the area

181
00:17:20,920 --> 00:17:24,040
and if you see them
or find evidence on them

182
00:17:24,280 --> 00:17:26,120
you'll alert me immediately.

183
00:17:26,360 --> 00:17:31,160
Okay. And why are they hot
on your trail?

184
00:17:33,680 --> 00:17:39,480
A certain something I have.
Let's leave it at that.

185
00:17:40,040 --> 00:17:43,160
What do they look like?

186
00:17:44,280 --> 00:17:49,160
Well, they wear dark clothes,
dark hats.

187
00:17:49,400 --> 00:17:51,400
They're kind of anonymous

188
00:17:51,640 --> 00:17:54,520
but you can recognize their cars

189
00:17:54,760 --> 00:17:58,320
Ioud and flashy.

190
00:17:58,600 --> 00:18:00,840
When they move, they move in packs

191
00:18:01,080 --> 00:18:05,040
like animals closing
in on the kill.

192
00:18:07,160 --> 00:18:10,600
And they cast long shadows.

193
00:18:12,320 --> 00:18:15,280
Oh, what a world.

194
00:18:18,120 --> 00:18:21,320
They're not cops, are they?

195
00:18:21,560 --> 00:18:24,800
Or secret agents?

196
00:18:24,840 --> 00:18:30,040
Are you asking me if I'm a bad guy
or a commie spy?

197
00:18:30,280 --> 00:18:32,400
I've scamped my share of fines

198
00:18:32,640 --> 00:18:35,280
and if there were library police

199
00:18:35,520 --> 00:18:39,080
I'd be one of their
10 most wanted.

200
00:18:39,320 --> 00:18:44,280
But I never robbed a bank
or stole a military secret.

201
00:18:44,520 --> 00:18:47,280
So who are they?

202
00:18:47,520 --> 00:18:49,920
They're thugs, relentless

203
00:18:50,160 --> 00:18:52,480
when they're after something.

204
00:18:52,720 --> 00:18:57,160
- Like this something you have?
- That's right.

205
00:18:57,520 --> 00:19:01,400
And what they want is me,
back under their control.

206
00:19:01,640 --> 00:19:04,720
Look out. When they're closing in

207
00:19:04,960 --> 00:19:08,040
they leave strange signs in code

208
00:19:08,280 --> 00:19:11,440
in obvious places
like telephone poles

209
00:19:11,680 --> 00:19:16,840
posters and notices
for lost pets and lost dogs.

210
00:19:17,880 --> 00:19:21,400
If I knew what they'd do,
they'd never catch me.

211
00:19:21,640 --> 00:19:26,120
- What do I do if I see them?
- Run and tell me what you've seen.

212
00:19:26,360 --> 00:19:29,560
Remember when I asked if you knew
what was going on around here?

213
00:19:29,800 --> 00:19:35,720
- Sure.
- That's why you're my man, kiddo.

214
00:19:41,520 --> 00:19:44,440
Don't worry,
I won't let the bogeymen get you.

215
00:19:44,680 --> 00:19:48,080
- Bobby?
- She can't know what you're thinking.

216
00:19:48,320 --> 00:19:53,600
You think she can,
and that's a mother's power.

217
00:19:54,320 --> 00:19:57,280
Mrs. Garfield.

218
00:19:59,120 --> 00:20:01,520
Well, it's very cozy in here.

219
00:20:01,760 --> 00:20:04,440
Mom, Ted... I mean, Mr. Brautigan

220
00:20:04,680 --> 00:20:09,000
he's gonna pay me a dollar a week
to read him the paper.

221
00:20:09,240 --> 00:20:11,640
Well, that's very generous.

222
00:20:11,880 --> 00:20:15,280
Do you always have boys read to you,
Mr. Brattigan?

223
00:20:15,520 --> 00:20:17,680
It's Brautigan, ma'am.

224
00:20:17,920 --> 00:20:20,560
And, yes, I need someone to do it.

225
00:20:20,800 --> 00:20:23,600
My eyes aren't what they used to be
since I retired.

226
00:20:23,840 --> 00:20:26,240
And what did you do before that?

227
00:20:26,480 --> 00:20:30,960
I worked up north. Various places.

228
00:20:34,680 --> 00:20:39,440
Well, come along, Bobby.
Time and tide wait for no man.

229
00:20:39,680 --> 00:20:43,360
- Bye, Mr. Brautigan.
- Bobby.

230
00:20:51,800 --> 00:20:55,320
Mom, guess what Mr. Brautigan...

231
00:20:58,600 --> 00:21:00,920
- Something doesn't make sense.
- What?

232
00:21:01,160 --> 00:21:04,560
Why would a man his age wanna
spend time with a kid?

233
00:21:04,800 --> 00:21:06,560
I don't know.

234
00:21:06,800 --> 00:21:10,280
I do know that he said
I must be some lucky kid

235
00:21:10,520 --> 00:21:12,480
to have a mom who'd let me

236
00:21:12,720 --> 00:21:17,800
have a grownup library card
for my birthday.

237
00:21:18,000 --> 00:21:20,160
I don't know. I trust him

238
00:21:20,400 --> 00:21:23,400
about as far as I could
sling a piano.

239
00:21:23,640 --> 00:21:28,560
That's right, spoil it for me.
You never want me to get that bike.

240
00:21:28,800 --> 00:21:31,560
I do, and I wish I could've
gotten it for you.

241
00:21:31,800 --> 00:21:35,600
But your father didn't exactly
leave us well-off.

242
00:21:35,840 --> 00:21:38,960
It's only reading.

243
00:21:43,320 --> 00:21:46,360
All right, what's the harm?

244
00:21:46,600 --> 00:21:47,480
Yes, yes, yes!

245
00:21:47,720 --> 00:21:51,640
But only on the porch,
mind, in the fresh air.

246
00:21:51,880 --> 00:21:54,360
Okay.

247
00:22:09,600 --> 00:22:13,200
- Bye, Bobby.
- Bye, Carol.

248
00:22:13,800 --> 00:22:16,000
Sorry I'm late. I forgot the time.

249
00:22:16,240 --> 00:22:17,800
That's all right.

250
00:22:18,040 --> 00:22:21,480
We're all time's captives,
hostages to eternity.

251
00:22:21,720 --> 00:22:23,640
Ben Jonson?

252
00:22:23,880 --> 00:22:25,800
No, Boris Pasternak.

253
00:22:26,040 --> 00:22:30,440
He was a Russian
of no account, I think.

254
00:22:30,680 --> 00:22:33,840
What's going on in the world?
Something scurrilous.

255
00:22:34,080 --> 00:22:36,280
"Vice President Richard M. Nixon

256
00:22:36,520 --> 00:22:39,520
after having won
the Republican nomination

257
00:22:39,760 --> 00:22:43,880
on the first ballot,
confers with Henry Cabot Lodge..."

258
00:22:44,120 --> 00:22:49,400
- We're going for ice cream.
- Can't. Earning my daily bread.

259
00:22:49,640 --> 00:22:54,560
- Afternoon, Mrs. Gerber. Carol.
- Hi, Ted.

260
00:22:54,920 --> 00:22:59,440
I never, ever saw a girl
as special as Carol Gerber.

261
00:22:59,680 --> 00:23:01,000
There's millions.

262
00:23:01,240 --> 00:23:03,560
Oh, yeah?

263
00:23:03,800 --> 00:23:06,760
- Have you kissed her yet?
- Yuck!

264
00:23:07,000 --> 00:23:10,960
- Well, you will, I promise you.
- Stay away.

265
00:23:11,000 --> 00:23:14,920
You will. It will be the kiss
by which all others

266
00:23:15,160 --> 00:23:20,840
in your life will be judged,
and found wanting.

267
00:23:21,360 --> 00:23:24,120
Are you done?

268
00:23:24,680 --> 00:23:28,560
Yeah. Come on, read to me. Go on.

269
00:23:28,800 --> 00:23:33,560
- Come back here and do your job.
- Okay.

270
00:23:34,240 --> 00:23:37,280
But you will kiss her.

271
00:23:40,600 --> 00:23:43,880
Oh, my God!

272
00:23:51,400 --> 00:23:54,000
Nice going.

273
00:23:59,160 --> 00:24:03,440
Get in! Get in, Bobby!

274
00:24:27,400 --> 00:24:30,880
Come on. Come on, Sully.

275
00:24:31,120 --> 00:24:33,160
Sully!

276
00:24:33,400 --> 00:24:39,800
"FBI announces new measures
to combat Red infiltrators."

277
00:24:40,720 --> 00:24:42,840
- Hey, Bobby.
- Yeah?

278
00:24:43,080 --> 00:24:47,000
Tell me what Dale Arden's wearing
in "Flash Gordon".

279
00:24:47,240 --> 00:24:50,120
What is it with you and her?

280
00:24:50,360 --> 00:24:55,720
When I was younger I thought
she was a real hotsie-totsie.

281
00:24:55,960 --> 00:25:00,120
Okay, before comics,
we've got sports, baseball.

282
00:25:00,360 --> 00:25:04,360
"Maury Wills on the way
to break Ty Cobb's record."

283
00:25:04,600 --> 00:25:06,280
I saw Cobb.

284
00:25:06,520 --> 00:25:10,120
My dad saw Babe Ruth.
He saw him point for the home run.

285
00:25:10,360 --> 00:25:13,480
Against the Cubs.
He told me all about it.

286
00:25:13,720 --> 00:25:17,640
He tell you of Nagurski's
comeback game?

287
00:25:18,240 --> 00:25:21,840
I know he saw it, though.
Were you there?

288
00:25:22,080 --> 00:25:27,040
- Yeah.
- You and Dad were at the same place.

289
00:25:27,280 --> 00:25:29,680
You know about Nagurski?

290
00:25:29,920 --> 00:25:32,560
He was my dad's hero, that's all.

291
00:25:32,800 --> 00:25:36,320
The greatest football player ever.
He came to Chicago

292
00:25:36,560 --> 00:25:39,560
played eight years
to make the Bears champions.

293
00:25:39,800 --> 00:25:43,440
Then he retired.
When he was old, six years retired

294
00:25:43,680 --> 00:25:45,960
the Bears brought him back.

295
00:25:46,200 --> 00:25:48,920
Last game of the season,
they played

296
00:25:49,160 --> 00:25:52,320
the Cardinals, sworn enemies.

297
00:25:52,560 --> 00:25:55,680
The Bears had to beat
the Cardinals to win.

298
00:25:55,920 --> 00:26:01,960
Nagurski wasn't supposed to play.
Third-string fullback.

299
00:26:02,160 --> 00:26:04,680
In the first half
the starter went down.

300
00:26:04,920 --> 00:26:08,280
- The second half there was a pileup.
- Oh, no.

301
00:26:08,520 --> 00:26:11,880
If your dad was here
he'd say he was frightened.

302
00:26:12,120 --> 00:26:16,720
- He was just so scared.
- But why? Nagurski was in the game.

303
00:26:16,960 --> 00:26:19,440
I was scared too. We all were.

304
00:26:19,680 --> 00:26:22,960
We wanted a miracle, you see, Bobby.

305
00:26:23,200 --> 00:26:26,880
We wanted him the way he was,
the old Nagurski.

306
00:26:27,120 --> 00:26:30,640
We wanted him the way he was
in the old days.

307
00:26:30,880 --> 00:26:36,240
Did he do good?
I don't wanna hear this if he didn't.

308
00:26:38,000 --> 00:26:40,640
The quarterback gave him the ball

309
00:26:40,880 --> 00:26:44,280
and Nagurski ran slowly
up to the line

310
00:26:44,520 --> 00:26:46,720
and the Cardinals crushed him.

311
00:26:46,960 --> 00:26:49,520
But somehow

312
00:26:50,160 --> 00:26:53,600
somehow, he gained a few yards.

313
00:26:53,840 --> 00:26:55,320
Next play, the same.

314
00:26:55,560 --> 00:27:00,360
They just kept giving the ball
to the old man

315
00:27:00,600 --> 00:27:07,200
and the Bears began to move down
the field, five yards, seven more.

316
00:27:07,240 --> 00:27:12,360
If he could score for us,
we'd be champions again.

317
00:27:13,640 --> 00:27:17,960
Go on, Ted! You can't stop!

318
00:27:22,120 --> 00:27:24,360
Ted!

319
00:27:24,600 --> 00:27:28,400
Come on. I gotta know
what happened.

320
00:27:31,880 --> 00:27:33,160
Come on.

321
00:27:33,400 --> 00:27:35,600
You know what your dad did then?

322
00:27:35,840 --> 00:27:37,800
No, what did my father do?

323
00:27:38,040 --> 00:27:42,560
We were all screaming. We couldn't
believe what was happening.

324
00:27:42,800 --> 00:27:45,320
My God, what was it? Go on.

325
00:27:45,560 --> 00:27:50,600
It was our miracle, you see,
because he was crawling.

326
00:27:50,840 --> 00:27:54,160
Bronko Nagurski was crawling
toward the goal line

327
00:27:54,400 --> 00:27:58,240
and they did everything
they could to stop him.

328
00:27:58,480 --> 00:28:00,360
But nothing could stop him.

329
00:28:00,600 --> 00:28:06,360
Yeah, that's right, Bobby.
Not on that day.

330
00:28:06,720 --> 00:28:09,640
Not when your dad and I
saw the miracle

331
00:28:09,880 --> 00:28:13,720
when the old man brought us home.

332
00:28:14,720 --> 00:28:19,520
He scored. He scored for us.

333
00:28:20,040 --> 00:28:22,400
We were champions again.

334
00:28:22,640 --> 00:28:26,240
I just knew he would.

335
00:28:28,240 --> 00:28:34,240
Then he was gone again,
back to the North where he came from.

336
00:28:34,560 --> 00:28:37,560
Bronko Nagurski.

337
00:28:37,800 --> 00:28:41,960
Bobby? Bobby-o!

338
00:28:57,600 --> 00:29:00,000
- Ted?
- Yeah?

339
00:29:00,240 --> 00:29:02,880
Well, I know the low men
don't exist

340
00:29:03,120 --> 00:29:06,400
but if they started
driving around here

341
00:29:06,640 --> 00:29:10,880
and the signs started
appearing on the poles...

342
00:29:11,120 --> 00:29:14,920
Well, we both know
that couldn't happen.

343
00:29:15,160 --> 00:29:18,280
But if it did

344
00:29:27,120 --> 00:29:30,760
would you have to go away?

345
00:29:32,240 --> 00:29:35,680
It wouldn't be safe
for me here.

346
00:29:35,920 --> 00:29:38,400
And wishing cannot make it so.

347
00:29:38,640 --> 00:29:41,440
Bobby!

348
00:29:55,720 --> 00:30:00,200
Bobby? This Ted of yours

349
00:30:01,040 --> 00:30:03,920
did he say where he's from?

350
00:30:04,160 --> 00:30:08,520
Someplace not as nice as here,
I think.

351
00:30:09,680 --> 00:30:13,800
Well, that doesn't tell us much,
does it?

352
00:30:14,040 --> 00:30:18,760
- Anything else?
- Nope.

353
00:30:21,240 --> 00:30:23,680
Bobby?

354
00:30:26,680 --> 00:30:32,160
- Does he...?
- What?

355
00:30:35,320 --> 00:30:38,120
Nothing.

356
00:30:38,240 --> 00:30:42,560
You'll tell me if anything
unusual happens?

357
00:30:43,880 --> 00:30:45,200
Hello?

358
00:30:45,440 --> 00:30:48,160
Hi.

359
00:30:50,280 --> 00:30:51,680
You promised.

360
00:30:51,920 --> 00:30:55,080
I really need the...

361
00:30:55,960 --> 00:30:57,720
Who was that?

362
00:30:57,960 --> 00:31:01,920
Nothing, honey.
Just a wrong number.

363
00:31:07,440 --> 00:31:10,560
Son of a bitch!

364
00:31:32,320 --> 00:31:35,480
- I know it's you!
- Your mom says she's almost ready.

365
00:31:35,720 --> 00:31:38,040
- Think Ted would come?
- To the fair?

366
00:31:38,280 --> 00:31:42,200
- Don't you think we should ask?
- I guess.

367
00:31:42,440 --> 00:31:46,600
- You do it. I'll get Sully.
- Okay.

368
00:31:47,120 --> 00:31:52,560
- Do you like being beaten by a girl?
- Hey, no fair.

369
00:32:03,240 --> 00:32:06,160
- Mr. Biderman needs me to go in.
- On Saturday?

370
00:32:06,400 --> 00:32:10,400
- Some people have to work for money.
- Mom, you promised.

371
00:32:10,640 --> 00:32:13,800
These are just Kools.
Read the advertising:

372
00:32:14,040 --> 00:32:18,120
"Kools. They cool the throat."
They're hardly cigarettes at all.

373
00:32:18,360 --> 00:32:19,640
- Mom?
- What?

374
00:32:19,880 --> 00:32:21,840
Can I have money for the rides?

375
00:32:22,080 --> 00:32:25,680
You never stop, do you?
Aren't you earning money now?

376
00:32:25,920 --> 00:32:26,960
For the bike.

377
00:32:27,200 --> 00:32:33,640
If you want to spend it on rides with
your girlfriend, that's your business.

378
00:32:50,560 --> 00:32:55,880
Ted? It's me.
You wanna come to the fair?

379
00:32:59,840 --> 00:33:02,320
Ted?

380
00:33:19,280 --> 00:33:22,920
Is everything okay?

381
00:33:30,600 --> 00:33:33,840
Ted, wake up.

382
00:33:35,720 --> 00:33:37,880
Ted, you have to help me.

383
00:33:38,120 --> 00:33:40,760
Ted, I don't know what to do.

384
00:33:41,000 --> 00:33:43,880
They draw west now.

385
00:33:44,120 --> 00:33:46,720
Who? Jesus, Ted, please.

386
00:33:46,960 --> 00:33:52,160
They draw west now,
but they may be back.

387
00:33:55,360 --> 00:34:00,520
Ted, please.
You can't die on me.

388
00:34:00,840 --> 00:34:03,360
Please...

389
00:34:06,200 --> 00:34:08,480
Oh, my God.

390
00:34:08,720 --> 00:34:12,280
What just happened?

391
00:34:15,000 --> 00:34:17,480
I went off again, didn't I?

392
00:34:17,720 --> 00:34:21,160
- You mean, like at the fridge?
- Yeah.

393
00:34:21,400 --> 00:34:25,400
No, way worse.

394
00:34:25,440 --> 00:34:29,680
I thought you were having a fit.

395
00:34:30,040 --> 00:34:31,440
It's all right.

396
00:34:31,680 --> 00:34:34,600
If it happens again,
don't touch me.

397
00:34:34,840 --> 00:34:37,560
Nobody should touch me,
that's all.

398
00:34:37,800 --> 00:34:40,840
Sorry.

399
00:34:41,800 --> 00:34:46,400
- Is it safe to leave you alone?
- Yeah.

400
00:34:48,160 --> 00:34:51,160
It's okay.

401
00:34:54,280 --> 00:34:56,920
Okay.

402
00:35:00,160 --> 00:35:02,560
Mrs. Gerber's taking us to the fair.

403
00:35:02,800 --> 00:35:05,960
Carol and I thought you
might like to come.

404
00:35:06,200 --> 00:35:11,840
Thank you, Bobby,
but I think just now, it's not wise.

405
00:35:12,080 --> 00:35:15,560
- Okay.
- Okay.

406
00:35:21,360 --> 00:35:25,080
The cigarettes are on the table.

407
00:35:25,840 --> 00:35:28,480
Thanks, kiddo.

408
00:35:28,720 --> 00:35:30,480
What's so funny?

409
00:35:30,720 --> 00:35:36,800
You run along now. Enjoy yourself.
Don't fall out of anything.

410
00:35:56,400 --> 00:35:59,840
Yes! That one.

411
00:36:17,640 --> 00:36:19,160
No!

412
00:36:19,400 --> 00:36:22,680
Yes!

413
00:36:23,520 --> 00:36:25,120
What are you gonna name it?

414
00:36:25,360 --> 00:36:30,360
All right. Step right up!
Hey, who feels lucky?

415
00:36:30,600 --> 00:36:32,800
Find the queen of hearts and win.

416
00:36:33,040 --> 00:36:35,640
- It already happened!
- Just once.

417
00:36:35,880 --> 00:36:37,520
Easy peas-y Japanese-y.

418
00:36:37,760 --> 00:36:40,760
Just find the queen of hearts.

419
00:36:41,000 --> 00:36:44,880
- Put down your bet. I'll do it again.
- A quarter.

420
00:36:45,120 --> 00:36:46,360
See, a jack.

421
00:36:46,600 --> 00:36:53,080
We got the king and we got the queen.
Tell me where she lands.

422
00:36:57,120 --> 00:37:00,320
- Fortune awaits you.
- That one there.

423
00:37:00,560 --> 00:37:01,800
- Yes!
- Genius.

424
00:37:02,040 --> 00:37:05,600
- I told you!
- Wait. Double and add a half-dollar.

425
00:37:05,840 --> 00:37:08,400
Okay.

426
00:37:17,400 --> 00:37:19,760
That one there.

427
00:37:20,000 --> 00:37:22,800
- Heartbreak.
- That's enough. I have to stop.

428
00:37:23,040 --> 00:37:26,440
- I can spot his moves.
- I better give up then.

429
00:37:26,680 --> 00:37:30,760
- Just a quarter.
- One, okay.

430
00:37:30,960 --> 00:37:35,800
Up and down, all around.
In and out, all about.

431
00:37:36,040 --> 00:37:37,360
Now they're back

432
00:37:37,600 --> 00:37:40,200
side by side.

433
00:37:40,440 --> 00:37:44,160
Tell me, mister.
Where's she hide?

434
00:37:44,400 --> 00:37:45,840
It's on the right.

435
00:37:46,080 --> 00:37:50,600
No. It's the one on the left.
Right there.

436
00:37:52,240 --> 00:37:54,120
- Okay, enough.
- There she is.

437
00:37:54,360 --> 00:37:56,560
- Bobby was right.
- A prodigy, huh?

438
00:37:56,800 --> 00:38:01,040
- Why don't you win it back?
- I could, but I can't play for money.

439
00:38:01,280 --> 00:38:02,200
A boast-y boy.

440
00:38:02,440 --> 00:38:05,360
Says he can win,
but afraid to back it up.

441
00:38:05,600 --> 00:38:09,040
I could have my money back.
Come on. Beat him.

442
00:38:09,280 --> 00:38:13,400
- I can't. Your mother won't be happy.
- Beat him, come on.

443
00:38:13,640 --> 00:38:16,760
My mom's never happy.
It's all I got.

444
00:38:17,000 --> 00:38:23,440
This is the move that stunned
the sheik of Araby. Behold.

445
00:38:31,360 --> 00:38:35,120
This one here, in the middle.

446
00:38:38,560 --> 00:38:41,840
- All right!
- That's it!

447
00:38:42,880 --> 00:38:44,000
A lucky guess.

448
00:38:44,240 --> 00:38:48,680
Double your bet.
That way we all go home happy.

449
00:38:48,920 --> 00:38:51,800
Fine.

450
00:38:57,000 --> 00:39:01,080
This one is five years of my life.

451
00:39:38,800 --> 00:39:41,880
This one here.

452
00:39:42,840 --> 00:39:46,440
Nobody ever beat that shuffle.

453
00:39:47,600 --> 00:39:51,720
Well, mister,
is it or isn't it?

454
00:39:53,360 --> 00:39:55,960
- Yes, that's it! Okay.
- All right!

455
00:39:56,200 --> 00:40:01,120
- It was a fluke.
- You bet it was a fluke.

456
00:40:03,200 --> 00:40:04,440
Now beat it, kid.

457
00:40:04,680 --> 00:40:09,760
Okay, gang, let's go. That's enough.
Come on, Bobby.

458
00:40:10,880 --> 00:40:13,000
Step right up!
We had a winner!

459
00:40:13,240 --> 00:40:17,400
It's easy as can be.
Easy peas-y Japanese-y!

460
00:40:24,560 --> 00:40:27,000
Yes, yes.

461
00:40:36,120 --> 00:40:37,520
Don't be afraid.

462
00:40:37,760 --> 00:40:42,720
When we swung out, I was afraid
we would fall to our doom.

463
00:40:42,960 --> 00:40:46,760
We're as safe as can be.

464
00:40:48,920 --> 00:40:51,400
What do you think you're doing?

465
00:40:51,640 --> 00:40:55,760
Well, I thought you wanted me to.

466
00:40:56,000 --> 00:40:59,280
I just wasn't ready, that's all.

467
00:40:59,520 --> 00:41:02,360
Okay.

468
00:41:03,960 --> 00:41:07,920
- Bobby, do it again.
- I better not. You'll tell.

469
00:41:08,160 --> 00:41:13,360
No, it'll be our secret.
Hurry, before we go down.

470
00:41:15,760 --> 00:41:20,360
Bobby, I'm dying here.

471
00:41:38,320 --> 00:41:42,280
Thank you.
That was the nicest thing.

472
00:41:42,520 --> 00:41:46,160
It'll be the kiss by which
all others will be judged.

473
00:41:46,400 --> 00:41:47,840
What?

474
00:41:48,080 --> 00:41:52,280
Sounded better when Ted said it.

475
00:42:10,400 --> 00:42:15,480
You knew, didn't you, where
the queen of hearts was?

476
00:42:15,720 --> 00:42:19,320
I could tell what was
going on in his head.

477
00:42:19,560 --> 00:42:23,440
Every thought he had, I knew,
and he couldn't fool me.

478
00:42:23,680 --> 00:42:27,680
Can you tell what's in Sully's head?

479
00:42:27,920 --> 00:42:29,680
Sully's head's always empty.

480
00:42:29,920 --> 00:42:33,880
Oh, yeah? Maybe I'm thinking
of getting a new glove.

481
00:42:34,120 --> 00:42:38,200
You are?
Well, what about that one?

482
00:42:38,440 --> 00:42:41,200
- Want it?
- Are you kidding? I love it!

483
00:42:41,440 --> 00:42:44,080
- Then, Bobby, it's yours.
- It is?

484
00:42:44,320 --> 00:42:47,920
I'll leave it to you in my will.

485
00:42:48,160 --> 00:42:53,480
- Sully, you just love doing that!
- I got you again.

486
00:42:54,080 --> 00:42:56,440
You know, when you're young

487
00:42:56,680 --> 00:42:59,440
you have moments
of such happiness

488
00:42:59,680 --> 00:43:03,920
you think you're living
in someplace magical

489
00:43:04,160 --> 00:43:06,040
like Atlantis must have been.

490
00:43:06,280 --> 00:43:12,240
- Carol, I owe you $75. It's your turn.
- Okay.

491
00:43:12,720 --> 00:43:15,120
- Here, give me $25 back.
- Twenty-five.

492
00:43:15,360 --> 00:43:17,040
- Here. $22.
- Okay. Wait, no!

493
00:43:17,280 --> 00:43:21,600
- No! Hold on.
- Oh, yeah. No.

494
00:43:21,840 --> 00:43:24,840
Then we grow up

495
00:43:25,520 --> 00:43:28,000
and our hearts break in two.

496
00:43:28,240 --> 00:43:30,640
- Yes! I own it!
- Wait, no!

